	<text>
		<body>
			<div>
				<pb facs="#facs_1" n="1"/>
				<p facs="#facs_1_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_1_tl_1"/>
					</lg>
				</p>
				<p facs="#facs_1_tr_2">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_1">Department of Philosophy,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_2"><date when="1950-04-18">April 18, 1950</date>.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_3">My dear <persName ref="gnd-116183853">Gertrud Bing</persName>:</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_4">Thank you for your good letter of April 5th.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_5">I have just had a word with the Librarian. During my stay in <placeName ref="geo-3996063">Mexico</placeName> I was</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_6">invited to come back to give a course of lectures; and the Mexican Minister of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_8">Education gave me a series of books on philosophy, published in <placeName ref="geo-3996063">Mexico</placeName> during</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_10">the last five years. They have now arrived; as we received two sets, we decided</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_11">that one should be sent to the <orgName ref="gnd-37543-3">Warburg Institute</orgName>. Some of the books are written</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_13">by prominent Spanish philosophers who, as refugees, are now teaching in <placeName ref="geo-3996063">Mexico</placeName>, -</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_15">the interest in philosophy in <placeName ref="geo-3996063">Mexico</placeName> is remarkable, and I have had many enjoyable</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_17">discussions. Several of <persName ref="gnd-118519522">Ernst Cassirer</persName>'s books have been completed there - one</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_18">has appeared long before the English or German editions will be out - and their</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_19">publication program is impressive, both in quantity and quality.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_20">Now to your letter.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_21">(1) <ref target="https://www.suhrkamp.de/buch/saturn-und-melancholie-t-9783518286104">Saturn and Melancholy</ref></l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_22">I am delighted to know that, at last, the publication is assured. Nelson</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_23">is a good publisher who will do his best to give it a good form.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_24">To make the publication possible, I will gladly forego royalties. On the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_25">other hand, I take it for granted that I may expect a fair number of free copies.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_26">As you say, there remains still some work to be done. I am very grateful</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_27">to you for your revision of the English text and for all that you will do. I</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_28">know the work is in good hands, and I am glad that you have enlisted the help of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_29">Mr. Kurz. Going through the first part, a short while ago, I saw again the wis-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_30">dom of our agreement that <persName ref="gnd-1029912939">Miss Labowsky</persName> should be asked to go through the text</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_31">where it deals with classical and mediaeval authors (and Renaissance Philosophy).</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_32">There are still some inaccuracies - often due to the process of translating of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_33">passages which, in German, have not a sharply defined,unambiguous meaning and</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_34">which, in English, convey an erroneous impression; without detailed knowledge</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_35">of the subject matter, it will not be possible to spot and remedy such passages.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_36">I have not got Dr. Frankfort's letter (of early <date>August, 1949</date>) with me and can</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_37">therefore not say whether she was to be asked to read the MS before it is given</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_38">to the printer or whether she was to see only the proofs. You will find the</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_39">letter, together with the form of title and the wording of the preface on which</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_40">we finally agreed (my copies of these papers are in <placeName ref="geo-2643743">London</placeName>). The procedure</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_41">then agreed to will make it possible for me to have another look at the book</l>
						<l facs="#facs_1_tr_2_tl_42">amd to have obvious mistakes corrected before the imprimatur is given.</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
				<pb facs="#facs_2" n="2"/>
				<p facs="#facs_2_tr_1">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_1_tl_1"/>
					</lg>
				</p>
				<p facs="#facs_2_tr_2">
					<lg>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_1">- 2-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_2"><persName ref="gnd-116183853">Bing</persName></l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_3">I am glad you aim at having the book published early in <date>1952</date>.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_4">I should advise to ask <persName ref="gnd-119144719">Einaudi</persName>,whether a translator has been found, how he is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_5">getting on, and when we may expect to have the first proofs. An inquiry on our</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_6">part will show him that we have not lost interest. Do you agree?</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_7">(2) Minio</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_8">I heard nothing more after writing to Dr. Frankfort on <date>March 14th</date> and sending</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_9">him a copy of my soothing letter. Is the matter now progressing to the satisfac-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_10">tion of all concerned?</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_11">(3) Galenus</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_12">In the correspondence of the last few months I cannot find anything relating</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_13">to the progress of the printing of the tick - pages. Could you kindly let me</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_14">know whether they have now been printed in<placeName ref="geo-276781"> Beirut</placeName> or in <placeName ref="geo-6269131">England</placeName>? I have not yet</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_15">received any proofs.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_16">(4) Proclus</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_17">As I mentioned briefly in reply to Dr. Frankfort's note of <date>March 24th</date>, it is</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_18">very disappointing that we should have lost over a year, waiting to obtain a</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_19">reply from Baylis. From Dr. F's reply I gather that he is in touch with a number</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_20">of publishers "and through them got to know more and more printers and binders".</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_21">I should be happy if you could tell me that the manuscript is actually with a</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_22">printer who has been asked for an estimate and for specimen pages.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_23">In two of my previous letters I suggested to ask the <placeName ref="geo-7288046">Cambridge University</placeName></l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_24">Press and the <orgName ref="gnd-123639271X">Northern University Press</orgName> for estimates. The first proved satis-</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_25">factory in the case of <persName ref="gnd-118686097">Alfarabi</persName> and there would be no difficulty whatever with</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_26">regard to the fount, etc; the second has been recommended to me. Has there been</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_27">any obstacle preventing us from asking these two presses, or have they been</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_28">asked in the meantime?</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_29">The part set up by Baylis (about which Dr. F. inquires in his letter of</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_30"><date>March 24th</date>) has been corrected. Actually, there was no particular hurry for</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_31">doing so since it cannot be printed without the Fontes. In any case, it is with</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_32"><persName ref="gnd-1029912939">Miss Labowsky</persName>; as soon as you want to send it (instead of the manuscript part</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_33">which is in your hands) to a printer, she can give it to you.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_34">I should be relieved of much worry if I could be assured that this matter</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_35">is now being given priority, and be informed which printers have been approached</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_36">meanwhile.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_37">(5) British Academy</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_38">I am going to write about this separately.</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_39">With kindest regards,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_40">Yours sincerely,</l>
						<l facs="#facs_2_tr_2_tl_41"><choice><abbr>RK</abbr><expan>Raymond Klibansky</expan></choice>/DV</l>
					</lg>
				</p>
